div.p:
The name of the village, Temry, which occurs for the first time, is not of much help as to its location. It means “the harbour” (see the Commentary), and, therefore, it could be located anywhere on a navigable river or its branches. There are at least two settlements whose names resemble the ancient one thus rendering them possible candidates for identification: Demrou/Damru in the Gharbiah governorate, roughly 25 km to the North-West of Bana, and Dimayrah, which is given as Demrou in the Atlas Géographique de l’Égypte, approximately 30 km to the North-East in a straight line.
For Damru, see Amélineau 1893: 505-506 s.v. Tiemrô and Peust 2010: 33, also known with the expanded name Damrū Khammārah. The name could be spelled in various ways: Damru, Damro, Demro, https://maps.app.goo.gl/6yhzBXAnRu9nkUz17;
Dimayrah/Demrou: https://maps.app.goo.gl/j8hNGGaPkzdRp1N59, accessed on 8 Apr. 2026. But cf. Peust (2010: 36) who gives an etymology from ϯⲁⲙⲏⲓⲣⲓ (‘the Nile-crossing’). However, from a topographical point of view, they would belong to the Upper Sebennyte nome in antiquity, which is a serious obstacle for their consideration. #fig5# #fig6#
